The paper deals with dynamic set intersection and graph algorithms, which are typically studied in the areas of data structures (cs.DS), discrete mathematics (cs.DM), computational geometry (cs.CG), distributed computing (cs.DC), and algorithms (cs.AL). The focus on maintaining a family of dynamic sets and supporting set intersection queries suggests cs.DS as the most likely category, followed by cs.DM and cs.CG due to the graph algorithmic applications. The mention of time/space tradeoffs also suggests cs.DC as a possible category, and the use of randomized algorithms suggests cs.AL as another possibility.
